snippet.textDisplay: The trailer for this popped up and I saw hanboks so I watched it through. All I can say is they better come correct with the Korean references made. As a Korean American young adult character in such a popular film, this well known character means something to other Koreans, like myself. I really hope they don't use our culture only for pure convenience. I want it to mean something, not just be "she's part Korean so let's throw in some hanboks" you know? I'm already not thrilled that they didn't cast the main character as someone who is actually Korean (or part Korean, as there are many KorAm actresses who go unnoticed and this surprised me since the author Jenny Han is Korean and I figured she'd want to include actual Koreans in the process, but that's another thing), but Lana Condor's performance was great so I commend her on bringing the material to life. But they threw in references to Korean BBQ in the first movie and the Yakult and that was really it. They can do so much with this and I hope to finally see some accurate Korean American representation by a film that has such a huge following. Time will tell. We shall see.
